In the PID controller:
1. Add integral anti-windup: when the computed output exceeds the actuator limits (PWM 255 or cmd_vel 0.8), stop accumulating the integral term.
   Example:
   - output = Kp*error + Ki*integral + Kd*derivative;
   + output = Kp*error + Ki*integral + Kd*derivative;
   + if (abs(output) < output_limit) {
   +     integral += error * dt;
   + }
   + integral = clamp(integral, -integral_limit, integral_limit);
2. Optionally smooth the reference trajectory to avoid large step inputs:
   + ref_smoothed += clamp(ref_target - ref_smoothed, -max_rate*dt, max_rate*dt);
At ~12s a large reference step causes the controller to demand maximum effort. All four PWM channels saturate at 255 and remain clamped there for the rest of the bag (~8s). The linear cmd_vel jumps from ~0.55 to ~0.8 and stays there, while the pose (x) continues to lag the reference (x). This is classic integral windup: the large sustained error accumulates in the integral term, the output saturates, and even after the pose begins catching up the integral term keeps the output pegged. The angular cmd_vel drops to zero after the step, suggesting the controller is entirely consumed by the forward error.
